---
# clang-tidy configuration for MindMap Helper
#
# This configuration enforces:
# - C++17 naming conventions (see docs/standards/CXX17_NAMING_CONVENTIONS.md)
# - Modern C++ practices (RAII, smart pointers, const correctness)
# - SonarQube rule alignment (see SonarQube Rule Mapping below)
# - Cross-platform code quality (Windows, macOS, Linux)
#
# Project guidelines: AGENTS.md and .cursor/rules/*.mdc
#
# SonarQube Rule Mapping:
# This configuration is designed to catch issues similar to SonarQube rules:
# - S1181 (Generic exception catch): Caught by cppcoreguidelines-* checks
# - S954 (Include order): readability-include-order (if available)
# - S109 (Magic numbers): readability-magic-numbers (ENABLED)
# - S3776 (Cognitive complexity): readability-function-cognitive-complexity (ENABLED)
# - S134 (Deep nesting): readability-else-after-return
# - S1231 (free() usage): bugprone-*, cppcoreguidelines-*
# - S5025 (Manual delete): cppcoreguidelines-*
# - S859 (const_cast): cppcoreguidelines-pro-type-const-cast
# - S3630 (reinterpret_cast): cppcoreguidelines-pro-type-reinterpret-cast
# - S5277 (Ignored return values): misc-unused-result
# - S1481 (Unused variables): misc-unused-parameters, misc-unused-using-decls
# - S1172 (Unused parameters): readability-unused-parameters (enabled via misc-unused-*)
# - S3670 (C-style casts): cppcoreguidelines-pro-type-cstyle-cast
# - S995 (Const correctness): readability-non-const-parameter (enabled via *)
# - S134 (Nesting depth): SonarQube rule (readability-else-after-return helps catch patterns)
# - S3776 (Cognitive complexity): readability-function-cognitive-complexity (ENABLED, threshold: 25)
# - S6004 (Init-statement): SonarQube rule (no direct clang-tidy equivalent, but readability-use-anyofallof for related patterns)
# - S6009 (String view): modernize-use-string-view (enabled via *)
# - S924 (Nested breaks): SonarQube rule (no direct clang-tidy equivalent)
# - S3972 (If/else formatting): SonarQube rule (no clang-tidy equivalent; see project coding guidelines)
# - S5827 (Redundant type, use auto): modernize-use-auto (enabled via *)

# Checks: do not add inline # comments here; YAML treats # as comment and strips the rest of the line, so the check name would not be disabled.
Checks: >-
  *,
  -abseil-*,
  -altera-*,
  -android-*,
  -boost-use-ranges,
  -boost-use-to-string,
  -clang-analyzer-*,
  -google-readability-avoid-underscore-in-googletest-name,
  -google-upgrade-googletest-case,
  -linuxkernel-*,
  -bugprone-easily-swappable-parameters,
  -cppcoreguidelines-avoid-do-while,
  -cppcoreguidelines-avoid-magic-numbers,
  -cppcoreguidelines-macro-to-enum,
  -cppcoreguidelines-special-member-functions,
  -cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-avoid-unchecked-container-access,
  -cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-constant-array-index,
  -cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-pointer-arithmetic,
  -cppcoreguidelines-init-variables,
  -cppcoreguidelines-pro-type-vararg,
  -fuchsia-*,
  -hicpp-vararg,
  -google-readability-namespace-comments,
  -hicpp-special-member-functions,
  -hicpp-uppercase-literal-suffix,
  -llvm-header-guard,
  -llvm-namespace-comment,
  -llvm-prefer-static-over-anonymous-namespace,
  -llvmlibc-*,
  -misc-include-cleaner,
  -misc-non-private-member-variables-in-classes,
  -cppcoreguidelines-non-private-member-variables-in-classes,
  -misc-use-anonymous-namespace,
  -misc-use-internal-linkage,
  -modernize-macro-to-enum,
  -modernize-use-trailing-return-type,
  -portability-avoid-pragma-once,
  -readability-convert-member-functions-to-static,
  -readability-identifier-length,
  -readability-redundant-inline-specifier,
  -readability-redundant-preprocessor,
  -readability-uppercase-literal-suffix,
  -readability-use-concise-preprocessor-directives,
  -readability-math-missing-parentheses,
  -readability-simplify-boolean-expr

# Note: The following checks are enabled to catch SonarQube-style issues:
# - bugprone-*: Catches bugs similar to SonarQube reliability issues
# - cppcoreguidelines-*: Catches code quality issues (except those disabled above)
# - performance-*: Catches performance issues
# - readability-*: Catches code smell issues (except those disabled above)
# - clang-analyzer-*: DISABLED for performance (see Disabled Checks Rationale)
# - misc-*: Miscellaneous checks including unused variables, const correctness

# --- Disabled Checks Rationale ---
# The following check families are disabled for project-specific reasons:
#
# LLVM libc checks (-llvmlibc-*):
#   These checks are designed for libc implementation, not general application code.
#   Disabling: llvmlibc-implementation-in-namespace, llvmlibc-callee-namespace,
#              llvmlibc-inline-function-decl, llvmlibc-restrict-system-libc-headers
#   Reason: They incorrectly assume libc coding standards should apply to all code
#
# Special member functions (-cppcoreguidelines-special-member-functions):
#   This project uses the Rule of Zero paradigm with smart pointers
#   (std::unique_ptr, std::shared_ptr) and RAII containers.
#   All memory management is automatic, so classes should not need custom
#   destructors. Enabling would incorrectly flag classes without explicit
#   destructors, which is correct for this project's RAII-based design.
#   If custom memory management is ever needed, use smart pointers instead.
#
# Abseil checks (-abseil-*):
#   Project does not use Google Abseil. These checks suggest absl::* APIs (e.g. absl::StrContains
#   instead of find() != npos). Disabling avoids NOLINT throughout the codebase.
#
# Altera checks (-altera-*):
#   Intel FPGA-specific checks not applicable to this desktop application
#
# Android checks (-android-*):
#   Android-specific (cloexec, temp-failure-retry). Project targets Windows/macOS/Linux desktop.
#
# Boost checks (-boost-use-ranges, -boost-use-to-string):
#   Project does not use Boost in application code. These suggest Boost APIs; we use std/STL.
#
# Clang Analyzer (-clang-analyzer-*):
#   The analyzer family (core, security, unix, deadcode, etc.) is among the most expensive
#   checks and significantly increases run time. Disabled for normal CI and pre-commit.
#   To run with analyzer for security/reliability audits, use a separate config or
#   -checks=... with clang-analyzer-* added for dedicated audits.
#
# GTest/Googletest (-google-readability-avoid-underscore-in-googletest-name, -google-upgrade-googletest-case):
#   Project uses doctest, not Google Test. Disabling avoids Googletest-specific suggestions.
#
# Linux kernel (-linuxkernel-*):
#   Project is userspace application, not Linux kernel.
#
# Fuchsia checks (-fuchsia-*):
#   Google Fuchsia OS-specific checks not applicable to Windows/macOS/Linux desktop app
#
# Other disabled checks:
#   -llvm-header-guard: We use #pragma once project-wide. This check enforces LLVM-style
#     include guards and has no option to allow #pragma once; disabling it is the way to
#     "teach" clang-tidy our convention (no NOLINT in every header).
#   -portability-avoid-pragma-once: Warns against #pragma once. We prefer #pragma once;
#     disabling matches our choice (same outcome as llvm-header-guard: no header-guard warnings).
#   -llvm-* (other): LLVM-specific style (namespace comments, etc.)
#   -google-*: Google-specific style preferences (namespace comments)
#   -hicpp-*: High Integrity C++ checks that conflict with project conventions
#   -readability-identifier-length: Project allows single-letter variables (i, j, x, y)
#   -modernize-use-trailing-return-type: Project prefers traditional return type syntax
#   -misc-use-anonymous-namespace: Some compilers/contexts require non-anonymous linkage
#   -readability-redundant-preprocessor: Nested #ifdef in cross-platform code is often
#     intentional for clarity; check flags valid patterns.
#
# Varargs (-cppcoreguidelines-pro-type-vararg, -hicpp-vararg):
#   ImGui, libcurl, POSIX exec*, snprintf, and fprintf use C-style varargs. Disabling
#   avoids hundreds of NOLINTs across UI and platform code with no benefit.
#
# Init variables (-cppcoreguidelines-init-variables):
#   Produces false positives for C++17 if-init-statements and variables initialized
#   from function return values or expressions. Disabling reduces noise across 34+ files.
#
# Bounds pro-bounds family (-cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-avoid-unchecked-container-access,
#                            -cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-constant-array-index,
#                            -cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-pointer-arithmetic):
#   All three pro-bounds checks are disabled for the same underlying reasons:
#   (a) Every flagged index is a loop counter or a validated node index provably in-bounds â€”
#       there is no real safety gap to close.
#   (b) The prescribed fixes (.at(), gsl::at()) throw std::out_of_range. All flagged sites
#       are in the per-frame ImGui render path, which has no exception handling
#       infrastructure; a thrown exception would propagate uncaught through the render loop.
#   (c) This project has no GSL dependency and no plan to add one.
#   If C-arrays are later migrated to std::array with validated indices the constant-array-index
#   and pointer-arithmetic checks become moot; the unchecked-container-access check would
#   still need to remain disabled unless exception handling is introduced.
#
# Bounds pointer arithmetic (-cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-pointer-arithmetic):
#   ImGui and SoA/path code require pointer+offset patterns (e.g. text.data()+text.size()).
#   Disabling avoids pure noise while keeping bounds safety elsewhere.
#
# Non-private member variables (-misc- and -cppcoreguidelines-non-private-member-variables-in-classes):
#   POD/config structs (GuiState, SavedSearch, Settings, etc.) intentionally use
#   public members. Disabling reflects design choice and avoids hundreds of NOLINTs.
#
# Math missing parentheses (-readability-math-missing-parentheses):
#   All 72 warnings are trivial `*`-with-`+`/`-` in vector and polynomial geometry code
#   (e.g. `cy + vy * t`, `a * p0.x + b * p1.x + ...`). Multiplication-before-addition is
#   foundational mathematical notation; parenthesising every term adds visual noise with no
#   safety benefit. The check was designed for genuinely surprising precedence mixing
#   (bitwise/shift operators), not standard linear algebra expressions.
#
# Local constant naming (LocalConstantCase, LocalConstexprVariableCase: aNy_CasE):
#   Both kPascalCase and snake_case accepted for local constants. Avoids ~150 renames and
#   NOLINT proliferation. See docs/standards/CXX17_NAMING_CONVENTIONS.md "Local Constants (Tolerance)".

# --- Platform Considerations ---
# This is a cross-platform project (Windows, macOS, Linux)
# Code is conditionally compiled via: #ifdef _WIN32, #ifdef __APPLE__, #ifdef __linux__
#
# clang-tidy running on any platform only sees active code paths for that platform.
# To verify cross-platform correctness:
# 1. Run clang-tidy on each platform
# 2. Generate compile_commands.json on each platform and run cross-compilation analysis
# 3. Use platform-specific build flags to test conditional code paths
#
# Note: Some platform-specific warnings are expected and acceptable

# Header Filter Regex:
# Pattern: '^(?!external/)(?!.*/curl/).*\.(h|hpp|cpp)$'
#
# This regex:
# - INCLUDES: All .h, .hpp, .cpp files in project (src/, tests/, etc.)
# - EXCLUDES: All files in external/ directory (third-party dependencies)
# - EXCLUDES: System/libcurl headers (paths containing /curl/) to avoid
#   misc-header-include-cycle and other diagnostics from third-party curl
#   (e.g. /Library/Developer/.../usr/include/curl/*.h on macOS).
#
# Third-party libraries excluded:
# - external/imgui/ (Dear ImGui GUI library)
# - external/nlohmann_json/ (JSON library)
# - external/doctest/ (Testing framework)
# - external/freetype/ (Font rendering)
# - external/vectorscan/ (Pattern matching library)
# - external/hyperscan/ (Pattern matching library)
#
# Rationale: Third-party code follows different standards and should not
# trigger project-specific checks. Enable manually for specific analysis.
#
# Generated embedded files (Embedded*.cpp, Embedded*.h) are excluded from
# clang-tidy in project scripts because they are tool-generated and very large.
#
# Note: HeaderFilterRegex uses POSIX ERE, which does NOT support negative
# lookahead ((?!...) ). So (?!.*/curl/) does not actually exclude curl paths.
# Use ExcludeHeaderFilterRegex to explicitly exclude system/third-party curl.
HeaderFilterRegex: '^(?!external/)(?!.*/curl/).*\.(h|hpp|cpp)$'
# Exclude diagnostics from headers under .../curl/ (system libcurl on macOS/Linux).
# Without this, misc-header-include-cycle and other curl header warnings appear.
# ExcludeHeaderFilterRegex: '.*/curl/.*'

CheckOptions:
  # Naming conventions (readability-identifier-naming)
  # Types (Classes, Structs, Enums, Typedefs, Type Aliases): PascalCase
  readability-identifier-naming.ClassCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.StructCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.EnumCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.TypedefCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.TypeAliasCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.TemplateParameterCase: CamelCase
  
  # Functions and Methods: PascalCase
  readability-identifier-naming.FunctionCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.MethodCase: CamelCase
  
  # Local Variables and Parameters: snake_case
  readability-identifier-naming.VariableCase: lower_case
  readability-identifier-naming.ParameterCase: lower_case
  readability-identifier-naming.ConstantParameterCase: lower_case
  readability-identifier-naming.LocalVariableCase: lower_case
  # Local constants: accept both kPascalCase and snake_case (see CXX17_NAMING_CONVENTIONS.md)
  # aNy_CasE disables enforcement so both styles pass; avoids ~150 renames and NOLINT proliferation
  readability-identifier-naming.LocalConstantCase: aNy_CasE
  readability-identifier-naming.LocalConstexprVariableCase: aNy_CasE
  
  # Member Variables: snake_case_ (with trailing underscore)
  # ENABLED: Member variable naming checks with suffix support
  # Note: clang-tidy's readability-identifier-naming supports MemberSuffix option
  # to enforce trailing underscores. This will catch violations of the snake_case_
  # convention (e.g., fileIndex, FileIndex, file_index without underscore).
  readability-identifier-naming.MemberCase: lower_case
  readability-identifier-naming.PrivateMemberCase: lower_case
  readability-identifier-naming.ProtectedMemberCase: lower_case
  readability-identifier-naming.PublicMemberCase: lower_case
  # Suffix enforcement for member variables (trailing underscore).
  # MemberSuffix applies to the base MemberCase rule; PrivateMemberSuffix /
  # ProtectedMemberSuffix / PublicMemberSuffix are required for the overriding
  # per-visibility rules â€” without them those checks evaluate the full name
  # (including the trailing _) against lower_case and falsely flag it.
  readability-identifier-naming.MemberSuffix: '_'
  readability-identifier-naming.PrivateMemberSuffix: '_'
  readability-identifier-naming.ProtectedMemberSuffix: '_'
  readability-identifier-naming.PublicMemberSuffix: '_'
  
  # Global Variables: g_snake_case
  # Global/constants use CamelCase with a 'k' prefix to enforce kPascalCase
  readability-identifier-naming.GlobalConstantCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.GlobalConstantPrefix: 'k'
  readability-identifier-naming.GlobalVariableCase: lower_case
  # Note: The 'g_' prefix is not directly enforceable via clang-tidy naming checks
  # Consider using a custom check or manual review for this
  
  # Constants: kPascalCase (recommended) or UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (acceptable)
  # We'll enforce kPascalCase with a 'k' prefix
  readability-identifier-naming.ConstantCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.ConstantPrefix: 'k'
  readability-identifier-naming.ConstantMemberCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.ConstantMemberPrefix: 'k'
  readability-identifier-naming.StaticConstantCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.StaticConstantPrefix: 'k'
  
  # Namespaces: snake_case
  readability-identifier-naming.NamespaceCase: lower_case
  
  # Macros: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (Windows API macros are exempt)
  readability-identifier-naming.MacroDefinitionCase: UPPER_CASE
  
  # Other
  readability-identifier-naming.EnumConstantCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.UnionCase: CamelCase
  readability-identifier-naming.UnionMemberCase: lower_case
  
  # Include order enforcement
  # Standard C++ include order:
  # 1. #pragma once (or header guards)
  # 2. System includes (<iostream>, <string>, etc.)
  # 3. Project includes ("MyClass.h", etc.)
  # 4. Forward declarations
  # Note: readability-include-order check may not be available in all clang-tidy versions
  # The check is configured but may need to be enabled explicitly if available
  
  # Magic numbers enforcement (S109)
  # Ignore common integer values that are self-explanatory
  readability-magic-numbers.IgnoredIntegerValues: '0;1;-1;2;3;4;8;16;32;64;128;256;512;1024'
  # Ignore powers of 2 (common in bit operations, buffer sizes)
  readability-magic-numbers.IgnorePowersOf2IntegerValues: true
  # Ignore common floating point values (including UI constants)
  # UI constants: 0.2, 0.25, 0.3, 0.35, 0.4, 0.5, 0.7, 0.8 are common in ImGui code (percentages, ratios)
  # Standard values: 0.0, 0.5, 1.0, -1.0, 2.0, 100.0 are self-explanatory
  readability-magic-numbers.IgnoredFloatingPointValues: '0.0;0.2;0.25;0.3;0.35;0.4;0.5;0.7;0.8;1.0;-1.0;2.0;3.0;100.0'
  # Don't ignore all floating point values (we want to catch magic floats)
  readability-magic-numbers.IgnoreAllFloatingPointValues: false
  # Ignore magic numbers in template arguments (common pattern)
  readability-magic-numbers.IgnoreNumericTemplateArguments: true
  # Ignore magic numbers in array sizes (often self-explanatory)
  readability-magic-numbers.IgnoreArrayIndexes: false
  # Ignore magic numbers in raw string literals (file paths, etc.)
  readability-magic-numbers.IgnoreUserDefinedLiterals: false
  
  # --- ImGui Considerations ---
  # This project uses Dear ImGui for the GUI, which has some unconventional APIs:
  # - Variadic argument functions (ImGui::TextWrapped, ImGui::Selectable, etc.)
  # - Magic numbers for UI sizing (0.0-1.0 for percentages and ratios)
  # - Immediate mode paradigm (UI rebuilt every frame)
  #
  # Related checks:
  # - cppcoreguidelines-pro-type-vararg, hicpp-vararg: DISABLED (ImGui and C APIs use varargs; see Disabled Checks Rationale)
  # - readability-magic-numbers: CONFIGURED with 0.0-1.0 allowed for UI constants
  # (see IgnoredFloatingPointValues above)
  #
  # See docs/design/IMGUI_IMMEDIATE_MODE_PARADIGM.md for ImGui patterns
  
  # Cognitive complexity enforcement (SonarQube cpp:S3776)
  # Threshold: 25 (matches SonarQube limit)
  #
  # Rationale:
  # - General code: Keep under 15 for maintainability
  # - Performance-critical code: Up to 25 acceptable for SIMD/parallelization logic
  # - Example: SearchEngine SIMD implementations intentionally exceed 15 due to vectorization complexity
  # - Example: ParallelSearch thread coordination code uses platform conditionals
  #
  # When exceeding threshold: Document with comment explaining performance necessity
  readability-function-cognitive-complexity.Threshold: 25
  
  # In-class member initializers (S3230)
  # Prefer in-class initializers over constructor initializer lists for default values
  # This prevents S3230 violations by encouraging modern C++11+ style
  modernize-use-default-member-init.UseAssignment: false  # Use brace initialization {} instead of =
  modernize-use-default-member-init.IgnoreMacros: true     # Ignore members declared in macros
  
  # --- RAII and Smart Pointer Enforcement ---
# This project emphasizes RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization)
# and explicitly forbids manual memory management (see project coding guidelines)
  #
  # Related checks (enabled via modernize-* and cppcoreguidelines-*):
  # - modernize-make-unique: Prefer std::make_unique over new/delete
  # - modernize-make-shared: Prefer std::make_shared over new
  # - cppcoreguidelines-owning-memory: Track ownership via gsl::owner (rarely needed)
  # - cppcoreguidelines-no-malloc: Forbid malloc/free
  #
  # Forbidden patterns (will trigger warnings):
  # - new T() / delete ptr  (use std::make_unique instead)
  # - malloc / free (use std::vector or std::string instead)
  # - raw new[] / delete[] (use std::array or std::vector instead)
  #
# See the project coding guidelines for details on memory management requirements
  
  # SonarQube-style checks configuration
  # These checks are enabled by default via the '*' wildcard in Checks section
  # The following notes map SonarQube rules to clang-tidy checks:
  #
  # Enabled checks that catch SonarQube issues:
  # - bugprone-*: Catches bugs (S1231 free(), S5025 delete, etc.)
  # - cppcoreguidelines-pro-type-*: Catches unsafe casts (S859, S3630, S3670)
  # - cppcoreguidelines-*: Catches code quality issues
  # - misc-unused-*: Catches unused variables/parameters (S1481, S1172)
  # - readability-unused-parameters: Catches unused function parameters (S1172)
  # - readability-else-after-return: Catches deep nesting patterns (S134)
  # - readability-non-const-parameter: Catches const correctness issues (S995)
  # - readability-use-anyofallof: Catches patterns that could use std::any_of/all_of (related to S6004)
  # - modernize-use-string-view: Catches string view usage issues (S6009)
  # - modernize-use-default-member-init: Catches in-class initializer issues (S3230) - ENABLED via *
  # - bugprone-redundant-branch-condition: Catches redundant nested conditions (S1066) - ENABLED via bugprone-*
  # - cppcoreguidelines-avoid-non-const-global-variables: Catches non-const globals (S5421) - ENABLED via cppcoreguidelines-*
  # - clang-analyzer-*: DISABLED for performance (see Disabled Checks Rationale)
  # Note: S134 (Nesting depth), S6004 (Init-statement), and S924 (Nested breaks) 
  #       are caught by SonarQube. S3776 (Cognitive complexity) is now enforced by 
  #       readability-function-cognitive-complexity (threshold: 25).
  #
  # Note: Some SonarQube rules don't have direct clang-tidy equivalents:
  # - S1181 (Generic exception catch): Manual review needed
  # - S954 (Include order): readability-include-order (if available)
  # - S1192 (Code duplication): Use other tools (e.g., PMD CPD)
  # - S3776 (Cognitive complexity): readability-function-cognitive-complexity (ENABLED, threshold: 25)
  # - S109 (Magic numbers): readability-magic-numbers (ENABLED, with common values ignored)
# - S134 (Nesting depth): No direct clang-tidy check (readability-else-after-return helps indirectly)
# - S924 (Nested breaks): No clang-tidy equivalent (SonarQube-only)
# - S6004 (Init-statements): No clang-tidy equivalent (SonarQube-only)
# - S3972 (If/else formatting): No clang-tidy equivalent (SonarQube-only; guideline in AGENTS.md)
# - S5827 (Redundant type): modernize-use-auto (enabled via *)

# --- Enforcement Strategy ---
# The project follows a phased approach to enforce code quality:
#
# Phase 1 (Current): WARNINGS ONLY
# - clang-tidy runs on all code
# - Warnings reported but not treated as errors
# - Developers address warnings voluntarily or during code review
# - Goal: Establish patterns and baselines
#
# Phase 2 (Future): WARNINGS AS ERRORS for critical categories
# - Enable WarningsAsErrors for high-severity checks
# - Target categories: bugprone-*, cppcoreguidelines-pro-type-*
# - Prevents new issues while allowing existing warnings to be grandfathered
#
# Phase 3 (Future): WARNINGS AS ERRORS for all checks
# - Enable globally to achieve zero-warning state
# - May require fine-tuning with pragma suppression
#
# Current Configuration (Phase 1):
# Warnings as errors (optional - can be disabled for gradual adoption)
WarningsAsErrors: ''

# Example Phase 2 configuration (commented for future use):
# WarningsAsErrors: 'bugprone-*,cppcoreguidelines-pro-type-*,misc-unused-*'

# System headers to ignore
SystemHeaders: false

# User headers to check
User: ''

# --- Verification Commands ---
# Run these commands to verify clang-tidy configuration is working correctly:
#
# 1. Generate compile_commands.json (required for clang-tidy):
#    cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_EXPORT_COMPILE_COMMANDS=ON
#
# 2. Test on single file:
#    clang-tidy -p build path/to/SourceFile.cpp
#
# 3. List all enabled checks:
#    clang-tidy -p build --list-checks 2>&1 | wc -l
#
# 4. Test specific check:
#    clang-tidy -p build --checks='readability-identifier-naming' path/to/SourceFile.cpp
#
# 5. Run on all source files (Linux/macOS), excluding third_party/external:
#    find src -name "*.cpp" -not -path "*/external/*" | xargs clang-tidy -p build
#
# 6. Fix issues automatically (where applicable):
#    clang-tidy -p build -fix path/to/SourceFile.cpp
